# Lithrim — environment template.
#
# This file is a TEMPLATE and is the ONLY env file checked into git. Copy it to
# `.env` and fill in your own values. Your real `.env`, `.live_env`, and
# `.connector_env` are gitignored — they stay local and never enter the repo.
#
#     cp .env.example .env
#
# Nothing leaves your machine: Lithrim is self-hosted, there is no hosted
# inference and no telemetry. You provide the key; Lithrim provides the harness.

# ── The demo needs NOTHING ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# `make demo` is a $0 replay of the flagship loop — no key, no network, no pack.
# You can run it on a fresh clone before setting any of the below.

# ── Live grading (BYOK) — bring your own model key ────────────────────────────
# Pick a provider, then set its key. OpenAI:
LITHRIM_LLM_PROVIDER=openai
OPENAI_API_KEY=

# ...or Azure OpenAI (set LITHRIM_LLM_PROVIDER=azure and these instead):
# LITHRIM_LLM_PROVIDER=azure
# AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY=
# AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT=https://YOUR-RESOURCE.openai.azure.com/
# AZURE_OPENAI_API_VERSION=2024-02-15-preview
# AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT=

# ── Exposing the BFF (optional) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Leave unset for local single-user (the gate is OFF, the one-command run is
# unchanged). Set it to require a Bearer token on every BFF request when you put
# the server on a network — pass it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` (or `X-API-Key`).
# /health and CORS preflight stay open. Point the shell at it with VITE_BFF_TOKEN.
# LITHRIM_BFF_TOKEN=

# ── Where in-app provider keys/bindings persist (optional) ────────────────────
# The keys + per-role judge bindings + chat binding you configure in the Connect AI
# panel are written to a gitignored `.provider_env` (+ a `.models_registry.json`
# sidecar). LITHRIM_PROVIDER_ENV_DIR sets WHERE they live. In Docker it defaults to
# `/app/out` = the named volume, so they SURVIVE `docker compose down`/`up` (wiped
# only by `down -v`). Unset locally → the repo root (dev back-compat, == old behavior).
# LITHRIM_PROVIDER_ENV_DIR=/app/out

# ── External domain packs (optional) ──────────────────────────────────────────
# A domain is a pack that loads from OUTSIDE this repo. Point at the dir(s) that
# hold it, then pin which one is active. With neither set, the core stays on the
# neutral built-in `_core` pack and grades fine.
# NOTE (Docker): a host path here is NOT visible inside the containers — for
# `docker compose up`, drop the pack folder into ./packs-dropin/ instead (it is
# bind-mounted; compose defaults LITHRIM_BENCH_PACKS_DIR to /dropin-packs).
# LITHRIM_BENCH_PACKS_DIR=/path/to/your/packs
# LITHRIM_BENCH_PACK=your_pack_name

# ── JUTE mapper add-on (BUNDLED, on by default) ───────────────────────────────
# The JUTE mapper ingests arbitrary/nested agent-trace + clinical JSON (paste a dump
# → it maps the trace → eval cases). As of CE Build C it is BUNDLED — `docker compose
# up` starts a `jute` service from a public SQLite-backed image (no auth, no Postgres)
# and the BFF reaches it at http://jute:3000 by default. Nothing to set. The core CE +
# grading + the clean demo also work WITHOUT it (`docker compose up bff ui`). Override
# only to point at your OWN mapper. See docs/JUTE_MAPPER_ADDON.md.
#   bundled compose service (default): http://jute:3000
#   host-run mapper from Docker:       http://host.docker.internal:3031
#   a remote mapper:                   http://my-mapper.internal:3031
# LITHRIM_JUTE_URL=http://jute:3000
#
# JUTE_IMAGE — override the bundled mapper image (default: a digest-pinned
# ghcr.io/etlp-clj/etlp-mapper@sha256:… build of the feat-sqlite-backend tag)
# with your own build.
# JUTE_IMAGE=
